<DocsPageSubtitle>
    Examples
</DocsPageSubtitle>

<DocsPageSection>
    <DocsPageSectionHeader Title="Column chart">
        Use a column chart to compare category values vertically.
    </DocsPageSectionHeader>
    <DocsPageSectionContent Code="SvgColumnChartExample" Outlined FullWidth>
        <SvgColumnChartExample />
    </DocsPageSectionContent>
</DocsPageSection>

<DocsPageSection>
    <DocsPageSectionHeader Title="Bar chart">
        Use a bar chart to compare category values horizontally.
    </DocsPageSectionHeader>
    <DocsPageSectionContent Code="SvgBarChartExample" Outlined FullWidth>
        <SvgBarChartExample />
    </DocsPageSectionContent>
</DocsPageSection>

<DocsPageSection>
    <DocsPageSectionHeader Title="Point colors">
        Use <Code>Colors</Code> to assign colors by data point index. The first color is used for the first resolved value, the second color for the second value, and so on. If the color belongs to the item itself, use <Code>PointColor</Code> instead so the color follows the item when the data changes.
    </DocsPageSectionHeader>
    <DocsPageSectionContent Code="SvgBarChartPointColorsExample" Outlined FullWidth>
        <SvgBarChartPointColorsExample />
    </DocsPageSectionContent>
</DocsPageSection>

<DocsPageSection>
    <DocsPageSectionHeader Title="Line chart">
        Use a line chart to show a trend across ordered categories.
    </DocsPageSectionHeader>
    <DocsPageSectionContent Code="SvgLineChartExample" Outlined FullWidth>
        <SvgLineChartExample />
    </DocsPageSectionContent>
</DocsPageSection>

<DocsPageSection>
    <DocsPageSectionHeader Title="Interpolation" New>
        Use <Code>Interpolation</Code> on line or area series to control how points are connected. The default mode is <Code>SvgChartInterpolationMode.Linear</Code>; use <Code>Monotone</Code> for smooth curves that preserve point direction, or one of the step modes for stepped trends.
    </DocsPageSectionHeader>
    <DocsPageSectionContent Code="SvgLineChartInterpolationExample" Outlined FullWidth>
        <SvgLineChartInterpolationExample />
    </DocsPageSectionContent>
</DocsPageSection>

<DocsPageSection>
    <DocsPageSectionHeader Title="Area chart">
        Use an area chart when the filled region helps show magnitude over time.
    </DocsPageSectionHeader>
    <DocsPageSectionContent Code="SvgAreaChartExample" Outlined FullWidth>
        <SvgAreaChartExample />
    </DocsPageSectionContent>
</DocsPageSection>

<DocsPageSection>
    <DocsPageSectionHeader Title="Custom colors">
        Use custom color values when series should follow a brand palette or CSS variable.
    </DocsPageSectionHeader>
    <DocsPageSectionContent Code="SvgCustomColorsChartExample" Outlined FullWidth>
        <SvgCustomColorsChartExample />
    </DocsPageSectionContent>
</DocsPageSection>

<DocsPageSection>
    <DocsPageSectionHeader Title="Mixed chart">
        Use the base SVG chart component when multiple series types should share one plot area.
    </DocsPageSectionHeader>
    <DocsPageSectionContent Code="SvgMixedChartExample" Outlined FullWidth>
        <SvgMixedChartExample />
    </DocsPageSectionContent>
</DocsPageSection>

<DocsPageSection>
    <DocsPageSectionHeader Title="Stacking, interaction, and time labels">
        Combine stacked series, grouped tooltip interaction, axis tick callbacks, and time-formatted category labels.
    </DocsPageSectionHeader>
    <DocsPageParagraph>
        <Code>SvgChartTimeAxis</Code> uses ordinal spacing by default. Set <Code>Scale</Code> to <Code>SvgChartTimeScale.Continuous</Code> on line, area, scatter, and bubble charts when irregular time values should be spaced by elapsed time.
    </DocsPageParagraph>
    <DocsPageSectionContent Code="SvgAdvancedChartExample" Outlined FullWidth>
        <SvgAdvancedChartExample />
    </DocsPageSectionContent>
</DocsPageSection>

<DocsPageSection>
    <DocsPageSectionHeader Title="Continuous time axis">
